ATTR_NAME: Family Ties - Parent 2 Net Worth - Person
DESCRIPTION: The Net Worth Gold of an older relative (Parent2) of the person on the client record. The basis for the model was the Federal Reserves Survey of Consumer Finance (SCF). Some area level data was also used in the model, primarily when specific household elements were unavailable.

Green Living represents households that are living environmentally friendly. They use environmentally healthy products and services such as, eco-friendly soaps, detergents, and household cleaning products. These households eat organic foods, and potentially grow the food themselves. They may also be socially active by donating funds to environmental causes. Some of them drive vehicles that are considered "green" or hybrids.

This model uses element #7795 Stocks/Bonds and applies household inferred data on top of it.  The value of 01 is the same counts as 7795 Stocks/Bonds. The inferred modeled portion, values 2-9, uses syndicated survey data for the target variable.  The element outputs a relative rank indicating the likelihood of the household being interested in investments.  A value of '01' means most likely to be an Investor and '09' least likely. A value of blank means there is no information available about the household.

Indicates the total dollars purchased in the month of April within the last 4 years in the Household. The Buying Activity data has been summarized into a categorical level according to purchase activity. This removes certain point-of-sale information, such as SKUs (stock keeping unit) but allows visibility into types of purchases and buying behaviors within the Household.

ATTR_NAME: RFM - Number of Orders - Upscale Catalogs - Range
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the Number of Orders purchased from Upscale Catalogs within the last 4 years in the Household. The Buying Activity data has been summarized into a categorical level according to purchase activity. This removes certain point-of-sale information, such as SKUs (stock keeping unit) but allows visibility into types of purchases and buying behaviors within the Household. Upscale = Designer Brands, Exclusive, Luxury, etc. Examples are Lafayette 148 and AlexandAlexa

ATTR_NAME: RFM - Number of Orders - Upscale Catalogs
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the Number of Orders purchased from Upscale Catalogs within the last 4 years in the Household. The Buying Activity data has been summarized into a categorical level according to purchase activity. This removes certain point-of-sale information, such as SKUs (stock keeping unit) but allows visibility into types of purchases and buying behaviors within the Household. Upscale = Designer Brands, Exclusive, Luxury, etc. Examples are Lafayette 148 and AlexandAlexa

Indicates that someone in the household has had a baby in the last 12 months. When 12 months is reached, the element goes to blank.

The logic gathers the ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Those ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have a much reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.  This particular element may have 0 coverage in California.

ATTR_NAME: Probable New Teen Driver - Age Indicator
DESCRIPTION: The element predicts the household has a teenager who will start driving within months or has just started driving. The primary function of the element is to help auto insurance marketers identify new prospects at a time when consumers shop for insurance. This element considers the legal driving age in each state and provides information whether the teenager has reached the legal driving age or not.

Indicates the known number of children in the household.  Includes modeled/inferred data added to the value of '0 Number of Children' and includes the mode of the ZIP9 and ZIP to extend the coverage to 100%.
This element includes 2 fields, 7602_01 which indicates the number of children, and 7602_02 which is the precision indicating the level of data that was appended.
This 7602 Number of Children includes a calculated mode of Number of Children from the ZIP9 and ZIP which brings the coverage up to 100%.  The basis of this element is 9602 Number of Children PLUS.  Calculating the mode of the ZIP9 and ZIP can add data to all Number of Children values.
NOTE: For the HOUSEHOLD LEVEL children's data: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Number of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.

Indicates whether a household is owner or renter occupied.  This element includes 1) 8606 Home Owner/Renter, 2) an inference rule that fills in missing data by inferring renter coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended, and 3) a mode calculation of the ZIP+4 and ZIP.  
1) For the 8606 Home Owner/Renter portion, it is fed by property data, self-reported data and address data which indicates the home is owned by the household or rented by the household, i.e., home purchase date, loan information, some indications in the address field that would indicate the property is a rental. 
2) For the inference rule inferred portion, since the home ownership coverage in 8606 Home Owner/Renter is above the census percentage of home owners in the U.S., the rule only infers renters. 
3) For the mode portion, the most frequently occurring value of O or R for the ZIP+4 or ZIP is used.  Our nationally represented consumer file is used to do the mode calculation.
This element includes an indicator of the level of data appended.

Indicates the years a household has lived at their address.   This element includes 1) 8607 Home Length of Residence, 2) a model/inference that fills in missing data by inferring length of residence coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended, and 3) a mode calculation of the ZIP+4 and ZIP.  
1) For the 8607 Length of Residence portion, it is fed by Purchase Date of Home, Move Date, other information where a person has indicated their household's length of residence, or the source has inferred a length of residence from a first-seen date, the date a landline phone was connected, etc. 
2) For the modeled/inferred portion, a question on a syndicated survey file is used to target the inferred data.
3) For the mode portion, the most frequently occurring length of residence value of 00-15+ for the ZIP+4 or ZIP is used.  Our nationally represented consumer file is used to do the mode calculation.
This element includes an indicator of the level of data appended.

Indicates whether anyone in the household is married.  This element includes 1) 9609 Marital Status in the Household, 2) business rule inferences that create Inferred Married and Inferred Single, 3) inferred/modeled data that fills in missing data by inferring marital status coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended, and 4) a mode calculation of the ZIP+4 and ZIP.
1) For the 8609 Marital Status portion, it is fed by consumer self-reported marital data.
2) Inferred Married and Inferred Single, values A and B, are inferred based on business rules.Inferred Married - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there are 2 names in the household with gender of Male and Female, within a certain age range of each other, then marital status is set to A "Inferred Married".  Inferred Single - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there is only one name in the household, then the marital status is set to B "Inferred Single".
3) Inferred/Modeled data is used to fill in married and single values up to the household match rate.
4) Mode calculations of married and single at the ZIP+4 and ZIP levels are used to fill in married and single values to increase coverage up to 100%.

Inferred Single - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there is only one name in the household, then the marital status is set to B "Inferred Single".
3) Inferred/Modeled data is used to fill in married and single values up to the household match rate.
4) Mode calculations of married and single at the ZIP+4 and ZIP levels are used to fill in married and single values to increase coverage up to 100%.

ATTR_NAME: Date of Birth - 1st Person in Household (YYYY/MM/DD)
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the Year, Month and Day of Birth associated with the 1st ranked person in the household.  The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  
An estimated 11% of the matched records will only return a month and year of birth.
  If there is only a Year and a Month of Birth present in this element, the day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year, month or day of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Acxiom policy allows full DOB to be provided to clients for legitimate reference purposes and applications.  Providing DOB to support client marketing applications is not a standard practice due to the sensitive nature of the data, industry and consumer concerns regarding its potential misuse.  However, exceptions to this policy will be considered by Acxiom Management and Privacy Teams where a significant need for full DOB is demonstrated and where privacy and consumer sensitivities are addressed in the subsequent marketing use of the data.  Contact PIAUseCase@acxiom.com if complete DOB is needed.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|DD fields.

Indicates the presence of children in the household. Includes inferred data added to No Children Present to extend the coverage to the household level and includes the mode of the ZIP9 and ZIP to extend the coverage to 100%.
This element includes 2 fields, 7622_01 which indicates the presence of children, and 7622_02 which is the precision indicating the level of data that was appended.
This 7622 Presence of Children includes a calculated mode of Presence of Children from the ZIP9 and ZIP which brings the coverage up to 100%.  The basis of this element is 9622 Presence of Children.  Calculating the mode of the ZIP9 and ZIP can add data to both Yes Children Present and No Children Present values.
NOTE: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Presence of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.

Indicates the presence of children in the household. Includes inferred data added to No Children Present to extend the coverage to the household level and includes the mode of the ZIP9 and ZIP to extend the coverage to 100%.
This element includes 2 fields, 7622_01 which indicates the presence of children, and 7622_02 which is the precision indicating the level of data that was appended.
This 7622 Presence of Children includes a calculated mode of Presence of Children from the ZIP9 and ZIP which brings the coverage up to 100%.  The basis of this element is 9622 Presence of Children.  Calculating the mode of the ZIP9 and ZIP can add data to both Yes Children Present and No Children Present values.
NOTE: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Presence of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.

Indicates the Year, Month and Day of Birth associated with the person.  
An estimated 11% of the matched records will only return a month and year of birth.
  If there is only a Year and a Month of Birth present in this element, the day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year, month or day of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Acxiom policy allows full DOB to be provided to clients for legitimate reference purposes and applications.  Providing DOB to support client marketing applications is not a standard practice due to the sensitive nature of the data, industry and consumer concerns regarding its potential misuse.  However, exceptions to this policy will be considered by Acxiom Management and Privacy Teams where a significant need for full DOB is demonstrated and where privacy and consumer sensitivities are addressed in the subsequent marketing use of the data.  Contact PIAUseCase@acxiom.com if complete DOB is needed.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|DD fields.

ATTR_NAME: Date of Birth - Person Default to 1st Person in Household (YYYY/MM/DD) - Date of Birth
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the Year, Month and Day of birth associated with the person, defaulting to the 1st ranked person in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.
This element has 3 fields, 7624_01 is the Date of Birth, 7624_02 is the precision level indicating the level of match (person or 1st person), and 7624_03 is the gender.
If the year and month of birth for the individual appearing on your customer file is not available, the year and month of birth for the 1st person will be appended. 
To distinguish between the year and month of birth appended for the person and the 1st ranked person in the household, a precision indicator is also appended.    The day of birth is not included.
  An estimated 11% of the matched records will only return a month and year of birth.   
  If there is only a Year and a Month of Birth present in this element, the day portion of the element will be set to 00.   
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12. 
  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.   
  When there is no year, month or day of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MMDD fields.

Indicates the number of adults (18+) living in the household.  This element includes 1) 8628 Number of Adults, 2) a model/inference rule that fills in missing data by inferring number of adults coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended, and 3) a mode calculation of the ZIP+4 and ZIP.  
1) For the 8628 Number of Adults portion, it is created by tabling all of the adults in a household that are provided from all of the sources. The adults names, dates of birth, and genders are used to de-duplicate the table.  Then all of the entries in the table are counted, and that count is placed in the element. This data is directly related to the names that are in the 1st - 5th individual/household data and 2526 Inferred Household Rank. 
2) For the modeled/inferred portion, a question on a syndicated survey file is used to target the inferred data.
3) For the mode portion, the most frequently occurring number of adults value of 1-6+ for the ZIP+4 or ZIP is used.  Our nationally represented consumer file is used to do the mode calculation.
This element includes an indicator of the level of data appended.

Indicates the number of known people in the household, both adults and children.   This element includes 1) 8629 Household Size, 2) an inference rule that fills in missing data by inferring household size coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended, and 3) a mode calculation of the ZIP+4 and ZIP.  
1) For the 8629 Household Size portion, it is a sum of Number of Adults and Number of Children. 
2) For the inference rule, since the household size coverage percentage for 2 people in the household is lower than census, the rule only infers the value of 2 people in the household.
3) For the mode portion, the most frequently occurring household size  value of 1-9+ for the ZIP+4 or ZIP is used.  Our nationally represented consumer file is used to do the mode calculation.
This element includes an indicator of the level of data appended.
(Note:  There is a small percentage of Household Size (0.005%) that will not sum to Number of Adults + Number of Children.)
SUBCAT2: People in the HH - HH Size

DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the estimated household income in broad ranges. 
This income uses 9641 Income as it's foundation.  7641 Income 100% fills in the missing data in 9641 Income Plus with the mode of the ZIP9, up to 100% coverage.

Description of 9641 Income Plus:  9641 Income Plus uses 8641 Income as it's foundation.  9641 Income Plus fills in the missing data in 8641 Income with inferred income, up to the household level match rate, generally 88%-93%, but it depends on the client file.
Description of 8641 Income: 8641 Income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.  
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.

ATTR_NAME: Date of Birth - 4th Person in Household (YYYY/MM/DD)
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the Year, Month and Day of Birth associated with the 4th ranked person in the household.  The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  
An estimated 11% of the matched records will only return a month and year of birth.
  If there is only a Year and a Month of Birth present in this element, the day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year, month or day of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Acxiom policy allows full DOB to be provided to clients for legitimate reference purposes and applications.  Providing DOB to support client marketing applications is not a standard practice due to the sensitive nature of the data, industry and consumer concerns regarding its potential misuse.  However, exceptions to this policy will be considered by Acxiom Management and Privacy Teams where a significant need for full DOB is demonstrated and where privacy and consumer sensitivities are addressed in the subsequent marketing use of the data.  Contact PIAUseCase@acxiom.com if complete DOB is needed.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|DD fields.

Internal 'money seeker' source data, along with some investment elements must be populated for this element to be populated.

Three of the following interests must be populated for this element to be populated. Internal 'sports' source data, along with a number of spectator sports interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated.

These people show a high interest in the world of collectibles. Their collections are more than just hobbies. Internal source data and 3 out of several collectible buying activity elements and interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated.

These people show a high interest in their homes. They like to lounge at home or take care of items around their house. Internal 'home living' source data and 3 out of several 'items that are done at home' interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Items like crafts, cooking, gardening, home improvement, etc.)

These people show a high interest in doing-it-themselves. Rather than hire someone to do the job, they will do it; rather than take their vehicle to be fixed, they will do it; rather than buy a piece of furniture themselves, they will build it. Internal 'do-it-yourself' source data and 3 out of several DIY interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as auto repair, home improvement, woodworking, etc.)

Internal 'participant sports' source data and 3 out of several participant sports interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as plays tennis, golf, running/jogging, etc.)
Internal 'Upscale' source data, and 3 out of several upscale interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as arts, foreign travel, theater, wine, etc.)
Internal 'Cultural' source data, and 3 out of several cultural and artistic interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as arts, antiques, etc.)
Internal 'investment' source data, along with a number of investment, charity and self-improvement interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated.
Internal 'high tech' source data, and 3 out of several technology interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as computers, pc games, online user, etc.)

Internal 'simple living' source data, and 3 out of traditional interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as coin collecting, inspirational activities, natural foods, enters sweepstakes or contests, etc.)

Internal 'professional living' source data, and 3 out of professional improvement interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as career improvement, self improvement, online education, investing, etc.)

Internal 'broader living' source data, and 3 out of a variety of interest elements must be populated for this element to be populated. (Elements such as International travel, current affairs, theater, community activities, inspirational activities, science fiction, etc.)

ATTR_NAME: Home Market Value - Estimated - Ranges (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the market value of the home in ranges. The data in this element is data provided by our Real Property source. Home Market Value is populated through a waterfall process of real property data. Use element 8850 Market Value Quality Indicator to understand the waterfall level for each Home Market Value.   Level 1: If the home sold within the last year, the purchase price is used as the Market Value. (8850=1), else   Level 2: If the market value is still blank, Acxioms real property source provides the market values via a valuation model. The model is based on current sales comparables and some Multiple Listing Service (MLS) data in non-disclosure states. (8850=2)   Level 3: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then populates with the county provided market value. (8850=4)   Level 4: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then uses the assessed value. (8850=5) Note that assessed value is only a percentage of the market value. Please see the assessed value definition for more information on assessed values.  8850 Market Value Quality Indicator (RP)  1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.  2 = Real Property Source - AVM used to create the HMV  4 = Real Property Source - Assessor-Provided HMV  5 = Real Property Source - Assessed Value

ATTR_NAME: Home Owner Type Detail (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the specific type of homeowner: Company Owner - The property is owned by a company and not owner-occupied. These records are not read into our mart build, so there is not any coverage for this value. Residential Owner - Homestead Flag - If a Homestead/Home Owner exemption flag is present, then the owner occupancy is inferred from this data. The exemption (or discount in property taxes) can only be taken if that property is the primary residence and occupied by the owner. It is also known as the Home Owner Exemption. This is a tax break for people who reside in their home vs. renting it out to someone else. Investor / Individual Owner - The property is owned by an investor and not owner occupied. These records are not read into our mart build, so there is not any coverage for this value. Residential Owner - Mail / Site Address - Owner-occupied and the mailing and site address are the same. Inferred Owner Occupied - Records that could not be coded as an H or O. We used the AbiliTec address links and if the mail link and address link were the same, then we inferred as owner-occupied.

ATTR_NAME: Home Assessed Value - Ranges (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the assessed value of the home, in ranges. The assessed value is the amount, stated in a ranged array, at which the home was last assessed by the local government. Current assessed value, by range, of property (land & improvements) for taxation as determined by the county assessor. An assessed value is the dollar value assigned to a property for purposes of measuring applicable taxes. Assessed valuation is used to determine the value of a residence for tax purposes and takes home market value into consideration.     County assessments are done periodically, i.e., every 5 years, unless in the cases of an improvement to the property, such as building a home on the property, a home remodel, etc. which would cause a new assessment at that time.    This assessed value comes straight from the county offices, not manipulated by the source or Acxiom.

ATTR_NAME: Home Market Value - Estimated - Premier Ranges (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the market value of the home in ranges. The data in this element is data provided by our Real Property source. Home Market Value is populated through a waterfall process of real property data. Use element 8850 Market Value Quality Indicator to understand the waterfall level for each Home Market Value.   Level 1: If the home sold within the last year, the purchase price is used as the Market Value. (8850=1), else   Level 2: If the market value is still blank, Acxioms real property source provides the market values via a valuation model. The model is based on current sales comparables and some Multiple Listing Service (MLS) data in non-disclosure states. (8850=2)   Level 3: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then populates with the county provided market value. (8850=4)   Level 4: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then uses the assessed value. (8850=5) Note that assessed value is only a percentage of the market value. Please see the assessed value definition for more information on assessed values.  8850 Market Value Quality Indicator (RP)  1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.  2 = Real Property Source - AVM used to create the HMV  4 = Real Property Source - Assessor-Provided HMV  5 = Real Property Source - Assessed Value

DESCRIPTION: Indicates the market value of the home in ranges. The data in this element is data provided by our Real Property source. Home Market Value is populated through a waterfall process of real property data. Use element 8850 Market Value Quality Indicator to understand the waterfall level for each Home Market Value.   Level 1: If the home sold within the last year, the purchase price is used as the Market Value. (8850=1), else   Level 2: If the market value is still blank, Acxioms real property source provides the market values via a valuation model. The model is based on current sales comparables and some Multiple Listing Service (MLS) data in non-disclosure states. (8850=2)   Level 3: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then populates with the county provided market value. (8850=4)   Level 4: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then uses the assessed value. (8850=5) Note that assessed value is only a percentage of the market value. Please see the assessed value definition for more information on assessed values.  8850 Market Value Quality Indicator (RP)  1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.  2 = Real Property Source - AVM used to create the HMV  4 = Real Property Source - Assessor-Provided HMV  5 = Real Property Source - Assessed Value

Indicates the known number of children in the household.
NOTE: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Number of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.

Indicates if more than one family lives at a particular address. Single-family dwelling units are defined as residential buildings housing one family or household, such as a house. The building does not share an inside wall with any other house or dwelling. It does not touch any other dwelling. Multi-family dwelling units are defined as residential buildings housing more than one household. i.e., Multiple separate housing units for residential inhabitants are contained within one building or several buildings within one complex, such as an apartment building. Condos are coded as multi-family dwelling units.

Indicates if more than one family lives at a particular address. Single-family dwelling units are defined as residential buildings housing one family or household, such as a house. The building does not share an inside wall with any other house or dwelling. It does not touch any other dwelling. Multi-family dwelling units are defined as residential buildings housing more than one household. i.e., Multiple separate housing units for residential inhabitants are contained within one building or several buildings within one complex, such as an apartment building. Condos are coded as multi-family dwelling units.

Indicates whether anyone in the household is married.  This element includes 1) 9609 Marital Status in the Household and 2) business rule inferences that create Inferred Married and Inferred Single to increase marital status coverage. 
1) For the 8609 Marital Status portion, it is fed by consumer self-reported marital data.
2) Inferred Married and Inferred Single, values A and B, are inferred based on business rules.  Inferred Married - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there are 2 names in the household with gender of Male and Female, within a certain age range of each other, then marital status is set to A "Inferred Married".  Inferred Single - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there is only one name in the household, then the marital status is set to B "Inferred Single".

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 1st Person in Household - First Name
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the first name of the 1st ranked person  in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  This element includes 3 fields, Name 8610_01, Middle Initial 8610_02 and Gender 8610_03.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 1st Person in Household - Middle Initial
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the middle initial of the 1st ranked person in the household.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 1st Person in Household - Gender
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the gender of the 1st ranked person in the household.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 1st Person in Household - Gender
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the gender of the 1st ranked person in the household.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 1st Person in Household - Gender
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the gender of the 1st ranked person in the household.

ATTR_NAME: Date of Birth - 1st Person in Household (YYYY/MM)
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the year and month of birth associated with the 1st ranked person in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.
An estimated 3% of matched records will only contain year of birth data.

   This element contains no DAY of birth, but the length of the element is 8 positions (YYYYMM00).  The day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year of birth and no month of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|00 fields.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 2nd Person in Household - First Name
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the first name of the 2nd ranked person  in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  This element includes 3 fields, Name 8612_01, Middle Initial 8612_02 and Gender 8612_03.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 2nd Person in Household - Middle Initial
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the middle initial of the 2nd ranked person in the household.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 2nd Person in Household - Gender
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the gender of the 2nd ranked person in the household.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 2nd Person in Household - Gender
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the gender of the 2nd ranked person in the household.

ATTR_NAME: First Name / Middle Initial / Gender - 2nd Person in Household - Gender
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the gender of the 2nd ranked person in the household.
Indicates when the last name was most recently verified at that address. (Year and quarter)
Household has purchased products via mail. This element is from sources that explicitly indicate the household is a Mail Order Buyer. There is no indication of how the purchase was made.

ATTR_NAME: Age in Two-Year Increments - 1st Person in Household
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the age of the person ranked 1st in the household, based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.  
NOTE: Age data is calculated from date of birth.  The age calculated may be based on complete date of birth (year, month and day) or incomplete date of birth (year and month or year-only).  If date of birth is not populated, age elements will not be populated.  The exception to this is modeled/inferred age data, which is only in the PLUS and 100% elements, and is indicated as modeled or inferred.

ATTR_NAME: Date of Birth - 2nd Person in Household (YYYY/MM)
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the year and month of birth associated with the 2nd ranked person in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.
An estimated 3% of matched records will only contain year of birth data.

   This element contains no DAY of birth, but the length of the element is 8 positions (YYYYMM00).  The day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year of birth and no month of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|00 fields.

Indicates that a working woman is present in the household. There is a female in household with an occupation status not equal to Homemaker or retired. The absence of a positive indicator in this field does NOT indicate there is not a working woman in the household, only that the information was not available.

Indicates possession of VISA or Mastercard bankcard(s) in a household.

ATTR_NAME: Credit Card Indicator - Gas Department Retail
DESCRIPTION: Indicates possession of gas, department store, or retail store credit card(s) in a household. A department store card is like JCPenney, Sears, or Montgomery Ward. A retail card is like Home Depot, Victoria Secret, or Best Buy.

ATTR_NAME: Credit Card Indicator - Travel and Entertainment
DESCRIPTION: Indicates possession of travel and entertainment credit card(s) in a household. Travel and entertainment cards are generally used to pay for hotel, airline, and other business related expenses. Diners Club and American Express are the most well known T&E cards. Many banks have specific T&E cards in addition to their other cards (i.e., CapitalOne Venture, Citi AAdvantage World). A few of the airlines also offer T&E cards (i.e., Delta Airlines Skymiles, Southwest Rapid Rewards).
Indicates possession of credit card(s) of unknown type in a household.
Indicates possession of premium credit card(s) in a household. Premium credit cards would be Gold or Platinum level.

ATTR_NAME: Credit Card Indicator - Upscale Department Store
DESCRIPTION: Indicates possession of upscale department store credit card(s) in a household. Upscale department store credit cards would be high-end stores like Nordstrom or Neiman Marcus.

Indicates the presence of children in the household.
NOTE: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Presence of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.

ATTR_NAME: Date of Birth - Person Default to 1st Person in Household (YYYY/MM)

Indicates the year and month of birth associated with the person, defaulting to the 1st ranked person in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.
If the year and month of birth for the individual appearing on your customer file is not available, the year and month of birth for the 1st person will be appended. 
To distinguish between the year and month of birth appended for the person and the 1st ranked person in the household, a precision indicator is also appended.    The day of birth is not included.

If the age of the person is missing, the 1st person's age will be filled in. The 1st person is determined by InfoBase using a series of rules. To distinguish between the age of the person and the 1st person in the household, a match indicator (8627_02) is provided.

Indicates the known number of adults (18+) living in the household.  This element is created by tabling all of the adults in a household that are provided from all of the sources. The adult names, dates of birth, and genders are used to de-duplicate the table.  Then all of the entries in the table are counted, and that count is placed in the element. This data is directly related to the names that are in the 1st - 5th individual/household data and 2526 Inferred Household Rank.

Indicates the estimated household income in broad ranges. 
This income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.  
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.
This income element also has two other versions, 1) 9641 Income Plus which uses inferred data to fill-in the missing data in this income up to the household level match rate. And 2) 7641 which uses the mode of the ZIP9 to fill in the missing data in 9641 Plus Income up to 100%.

Indicates the estimated household income in narrow ranges. 
This income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.  
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.
This income element also has two other versions, 1) 9671 Income Plus which uses inferred data to fill-in the missing data in this income up to the household level match rate. And 2) 7671 which uses the mode of the ZIP9 to fill in the missing data in 9671 Plus Income up to 100%.

ATTR_NAME: Date of Birth - 4th Person in Household (YYYY/MM)
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the year and month of birth associated with the 4th ranked person in the household. The ranking is based on a series of InfoBase ranking rules.
An estimated 3% of matched records will only contain year of birth data.

   This element contains no DAY of birth, but the length of the element is 8 positions (YYYYMM00).  The day portion of the element will be set to 00.
  The valid values for the month portion of the field are 01-12.  When the year is present, but the month is unknown, the month portion will be defaulted to 00.
  When there is no year of birth and no month of birth present, the entire element field is set to blanks.
Although not reflected here, for non-real-time clients this element will be split into separate YYYY|MM|00 fields.

Open loans are determined through the application of a proprietary model that uses county recorder data and where the data is not available for the 1st loan an assumed 80% of purchase price is used as a proxy.

ATTR_NAME: Home Assessed Value - Actual (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the assessed value of the home. An assessed value is the dollar value assigned to a property for purposes of measuring applicable taxes. Assessed valuation is used to determine the value of a residence for tax purposes and takes home market value into consideration. County assessments are done periodically, i.e., every 5 years, unless in the cases of an improvement to the property, such as building a home on the property, a home remodel, etc. which would cause a new assessment at that time. This assessed value comes straight from the county offices, not manipulated by the source or Acxiom.

ATTR_NAME: Home Lender Standardization Code 1 (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates a numeric code that identifies the lender of the 1st home loan. The lender codes are numerical representations of the Lender Name. There are over 40,000 different codes.

ATTR_NAME: Home Lender Standardization Code 2 (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates a numeric code that identifies the lender of the 2nd home loan. The lender codes are numerical representations of the Lender Name. There are over 40,000 different codes.

ATTR_NAME: Home Lender Standardization Code 3 (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates a numeric code that identifies the lender of the 3rd home loan. The lender codes are numerical representations of the Lender Name. There are over 40,000 different codes.

ATTR_NAME: Home Line of Credit 2 (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the Home Loan Amount 2 (element 8568 & element 8747) is an open line of credit (HELOC). An open line of credit doesnt necessarily mean the property owner has borrowed the entire amount. It simply means that they have an open line of credit up to that amount.
ENCODE_VAL: Y = Line is Open Line of Credit

ATTR_NAME: Home Line of Credit 3 (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the Home Loan Amount 3 (element 8569 & element 8748) is an open line of credit (HELOC).    An open line of credit doesnt necessarily mean the property owner has borrowed the entire amount. It simply means that they have an open line of credit up to that amount.
ENCODE_VAL: Y = Line is Open Line of Credit

ATTR_NAME: Home Market Value - Estimated - Quality Indicator (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the method used to derive the home market value estimate. This element works in conjunction with the following single-sourced real property elements:  9750 Home Market Value - Actual  8583 Home Market Value - Premier Ranges  8438 Home Market Value - Ranges
ENCODE_VAL: 1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.

ATTR_NAME: Home Market Value - Estimated - Quality Indicator (Real Property data only)

Indicates the code of the make of the 1st vehicle in the household. Vehicles are householded using Last Name and Address Link. Vehicle purchase date is not available in the source data provided, therefore the most recent vehicle data received is the 1st vehicle and the next recent is the 2nd vehicle. If the client needs to know when the vehicle was last known to be owned by the household, use 9047 Vehicle Verification Date 1.

Indicates that someone in the household is a classic car owner. This includes any vehicle that is older than 20 years. The valid value is the model year of the vehicle. This could be a motorcycle, truck, or a car. Acxioms vehicle data does not fall under the DPPA (Drivers Privacy Protection Act). The DPPA prohibits the release or use of personal information about an individual in connection with a motor vehicle record. Acxioms vehicle data is not sourced from motor vehicle records. It is sourced from surveys, completed by consumers, which were sent due to a vehicle warranty purchase, vehicle service/repair or from a product registration.

Indicates the number of children in the household.  Includes modeled/inferred data added to the value of '0 Number of Children' to extend the coverage to the household level.
This 9602 Number of Children includes a household inferred model that brings the coverage up to the household level match rate.  The basis of this element is 8602 Number of Children.  Since the coverage of 8602 Number of Children 'greater than 0' is already near the census percentage, household inferred/modeled data is only added to '0 Number of Children'.
NOTE: For the HOUSEHOLD LEVEL children's data: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Number of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.

Indicates whether a household is owner or renter occupied.  This element includes 1) 8606 Home Owner/Renter and 2) an inference rule that fills in missing data by inferring renter coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended.  
1) For the 8606 Home Owner/Renter portion, it is fed by property data, self-reported data and address data which indicates the home is owned by the household or rented by the household, i.e., home purchase date, loan information, some indications in the address field that would indicate the property is a rental. 
2) For the inference rule, since the home ownership coverage in 8606 Home Owner/Renter is above the census percentage of home owners in the U.S., the rule only infers renters.

Indicates whether anyone in the household is married.  This element includes 1) 9609 Marital Status in the Household, 2) business rule inferences that create Inferred Married and Inferred Single, and 3) inferred/modeled data that fills in missing data by inferring marital status coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended.
1) For the 8609 Marital Status portion, it is fed by consumer self-reported marital data.
2) Inferred Married and Inferred Single, values A and B, are inferred based on business rules.  Inferred Married - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there are 2 names in the household with gender of Male and Female, within a certain age range of each other, then marital status is set to A "Inferred Married".  Inferred Single - When the marital status of Married or Single cannot be determined from a source and there is only one name in the household, then the marital status is set to B "Inferred Single".
3) Inferred/Modeled data is used to fill in married and single values up to the household match rate.

Indicates the presence of children in the household. Includes inferred data added to No Children Present to extend the coverage to the household level.
This 9622 Presence of Children includes household inferred data that brings the coverage up to the household level match rate.  The basis of this element is 8622 Number of Children.  Since the coverage of 8622 'YES Children Present' is already near the census percentage, household inferred data is only added to 'NO Children Present'.
NOTE: The children's names are not provided by the sources.  The logic gathers the children's ages from across all the sources into a table to net the data to only the children's ages that exist in a household.  Proprietary logic calculates the netting.  The resulting ages are then populated into the children's age elements, then counted to populate the number of children element and the presence of children element.  Sources that provide an actual Presence of Children also contribute.
NOTE: Household level Children's age less than age 16 and gender data in the state of California will have reduced coverage due to the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA) regulations.

Indicates the known number of adults (18+) living in the household.   This element includes 1) 8628 Nmber of Adults and 2) an inference rule that fills in missing data by inferring number of adults coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended.  
1) For the 8628 Number of Adults portion, it is created by tabling all of the adults in a household that are provided from all of the sources. The adults names, dates of birth, and genders are used to de-duplicate the table.  Then all of the entries in the table are counted, and that count is placed in the element. This data is directly related to the names that are in the 1st - 5th individual/household data and 2526 Inferred Household Rank. 
2) For the inference rule portion, since the number of adults=2 coverage percentage is lower than census, the rule only infers 2 adults in the household.
There is not an indicator in this element of which data is inferred.  If that information is needed, please append 7628 Number of Adults 100% which has the indicator, instead of appending 9628 Number of Adults PLUS. Or append 8628 Number of Adults and compare it to 9628.

Indicates the number of known people in the household, both adults and children.   This element includes 1) 8629 Household Size and 2) an inference rule that fills in missing data by inferring household size coverage up to the household level match rate of the file being appended.  
1) For the 8629 Household Size portion, it is a sum of Number of Adults and Number of Children. 
2) For the inference rule portion, since the household size coverage percentage for 2 people in the household is lower than census, the rule only infers the value of 2 people in the household.
There is not an indicator in this element of which data is inferred.  If that information is needed, please append 7629 Household Size 100% which has the indicator, instead of appending 9629 Household Size PLUS. Or append 8629 Household Size and compare it to 9629.
(Note:  There is a small percentage of Household Size (0.005%) that will not sum to Number of Adults + Number of Children.)
SUBCAT2: People in the HH - HH Size

ATTR_NAME: Income - Estimated Household - Broad Ranges - Plus
DESCRIPTION:
Indicates the estimated household income in broad ranges.
This income uses 8641 Income as it's foundation.  9641 Income Plus fills in the missing data in 8641 Income with inferred income, up to the household level match rate, generally 88%-93%, but it depends on the client file.
This income element has different ranges/values than the other income elements.
Description of 8641 Income: 8641 Income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.

This income uses 8641 Income as it's foundation.  9641 Income Plus fills in the missing data in 8641 Income with inferred income, up to the household level match rate, generally 88%-93%, but it depends on the client file.

Description of 8641 Income: 8641 Income is about 3-5% consumer self-reported via indicating their income on product registrations and website memberships, and about 95-98% modeled from the sources, based on a variety of demographic factors, including age, occupation, home ownership, and median income for the local area.  Acxiom blends all of the source income data (the self-reported and the modeled data from the sources) into the Acxiom household level income elements using several rules including recency, commonality, and hierarchy.

ATTR_NAME: Home Market Value - Estimated - Actual (Real Property data only)
DESCRIPTION: Indicates the actual (not a range) market value of the home. The data in this element is data provided by our Real Property source.    Home Market Value is populated through a waterfall process of real property data.   Use element 8850 Market Value Quality Indicator to understand the waterfall level for each Home Market Value.   Level 1: If the home sold within the last year, the purchase price is used as the Market Value. (8850=1), else   Level 2: If the market value is still blank, Acxioms real property source provides the market values via a valuation model. The model is based on current sales comparables and some Multiple Listing Service (MLS) data in non-disclosure states. (8850=2)   Level 3: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then populates with the county provided market value. (8850=4)   Level 4: If the market value is still blank, Acxiom then uses the assessed value. (8850=5) Note that assessed value is only a percentage of the market value. Please see the assessed value definition for more information on assessed values.    8850 Market Value Quality Indicator (RP)  1 = Real Property Source - Home sale price w/in last 3-15 mo.  2 = Real Property Source - AVM used to create the HMV  4 = Real Property Source - Assessor-Provided HMV  5 = Real Property Source - Assessed Value
